# Adding MobilePay to app using linking as an alternative to AppSwitch
Adding AppSwitch to an app made with expo required me to eject the project and port the SDK to React Native. Of course possible, but does take time. As an alternative I found MobilePay Link. The user experiance is almost identical to that of AppSwitch, and can be implemented without ejecting and in less time and with less risk. Tested to work on IOS and Android devices.

*App linking can possibly also be used in apps outside of the expo environment*

![MobilePay Linking](data:image/png;base64,)


## Solution overview
The app opens Mobile Pay using linking and requests the payment. The user will either pay or abort. To know if the payment has been fully completed or assumed aborted the backend must be pining an endpoint with MobilePay looking for the transaction.

## Initiate payment
Using expos API for linking to initiate the mobile payment. The Mobile Pay app will open and the user will then continue to either confirm or abort the payment. Note: The supplied phone number must be a **shop number** for the MobilePay account. Locking prevents user from modifying  the comment.

``` javascript
import { Linking } from 'expo'

Linking.openURL(`mobilepay://send?phone=${9999}&amount=${1.00}&comment=${'Order #9999'}&lock=1`)
```


## Verify payment

After starting the payment flow. The backend server pings the transaction endpoint. Looking for the specific transaction representing the payment identified e.g. by a unique ID or an order number that was set earlier in the comment field.  

Once the backend finds the transaction and verifies the full amount, the order can be completed.  

If the transactions cannot be found over a period of e.g. 2 minutes, the user could have aborted the payment and a message could be shown asking user to reinitiate the payment or choose a diffrent payment method.

[Transaction API endpoint](https://github.com/MobilePayDev/MobilePay-TransactionReporting-API#transactions-endpoint)
